File: The Supreme Court of Appeal has dismissed with costs former president Jacob Zuma's bid to appeal a ruling that could see him going on trial. JOHANNESBURG - Former President Jacob Zuma's attempt to stop his corruption trial from going ahead has been scuppered. The Supreme Court of Appeal has dismissed with costs his bid to appeal a ruling that could see him going on trial. READ: Zuma appeals to avoid legal costs The court says his appeal has no reasonable prospects of success. At the same time, the French arms company Thales also lost in court on Friday. READ: Zuma says his health a priority Thales challenged the validity of former NPA head Shaun Abrahams' decision to reinstitute charges against it. The Supreme Court of appeal dismissed its leave application with costs. Both Zuma and Thales can still approach the Constitutional Court.